entry.title: Ship No-Vary-Search header and hint
entry.content:
The way these two features interact is:

- No-Vary-Search response header allows the prefetch cache to use

inexact matching if the prefetch already has received head at time

of navigation.

- No-Vary-Search hint allows the navigation to wait for the head

of the in progress prefetch that has inexact match with navigation

URL based on its No-Vary-Search hint.



In order to ship we use an approach similar to

go/graduating-from-finch#optional-leave-a-finch-hook to allow

unshipping and return to Origin Trial by using Finch config

without requiring a binary re-spin of Chrome.



The following are added:

- a feature param enabled by default

(kPrefetchNoVarySearchShippedByDefault) attached to the feature

PrefetchNoVarySearch which marks No-Vary-Search response header

as shipped by default. Disabling this feature param via Finch

unships No-Vary-Search header.

- a base feature for runtime enabled feature

SpeculationRulesNoVarySearchHint disabled by default. This allows

us to turn off No-Vary-Search hint functionality in the origin

trial independently of No-Vary-Search response header

functionality

- a runtime enabled feature

SpeculationRulesNoVarySearchHintShippedByDefault enabled by

default which marks Speculation Rules No-Vary-Search hint as

shipped by default. Disabling this runtime enabled feature

via Finch unships Speculation Rules No-Vary-Search hint.



The kill-switch functionality will work in the following ways:

- to unship No-Vary-Search response header while allowing

Origin Trial to continue: disable

kPrefetchNoVarySearchShippedByDefault via Finch.

- to unship Speculation Rules No-Vary-Search hint functionality

while allowing Origin Trial to continue: disable

SpeculationRulesNoVarySearchHintShippedByDefault via Finch.

- to stop Speculation Rules No-Vary-Search hint functionality

in the origin trial: disable both

SpeculationRulesNoVarySearchHintShippedByDefault and

SpeculationRulesNoVarySearchHint via Finch.

- to unship both functionality for all including Origin Trial

users: disable SpeculationRulesNoVarySearchHintShippedByDefault,

SpeculationRulesNoVarySearchHint, PrefetchNoVarySearch via Finch.



Links to Intents to Ship:

- NVS hint: https://groups.google.com/a/chromium.org/g/blink-dev/c/TZSsl2iCuA4/m/5BVuLhoBCAAJ

- NVS header: https://groups.google.com/a/chromium.org/g/blink-dev/c/XnG5BF3uoeE/m/th2iMQcBCAAJ

entry.title: [X11] Eagerly initialize extensions
entry.content:
A major gotcha in X11 extension usage is the server must know

the client version of an extension before it can be used.

This is problematic because

1. It's easy to forget to send the client version.

2. If the extension is needed in multiple places, it must be

redundantly initialized many times.

3. Initializing requires a sync if the server version is needed.

(This can be reduced to a single round trip if extensions are

all initialized at the same time.)



This CL consolidates extension initialization to Connection.

Unfortunately, each extension has a different interface, so

we can't move the initialization code to gen_xproto.py.

Instead, each extension must be hand-initaialized.



R=sky

entry.title: [A11y] Pause AX tree building for unrendered subtrees until it is parsed
entry.content:
Unrendered SubtreeIsAttached() signals are received for new unrendered

subtrees, causing the a11y engine to defer a children changed on their

parent, and causing the next ProcessDeferredAccessibilityEvents()

call to build out the AX subtree for that content.



However, if the document is still loading, we will sometimes get the

SubtreeIsAttached() when only part of the unrendered content has

loaded. In this case the AX subtree could be built incompletely.

Because the content is unrendered, there are no follow-up

NodeIsAttached() signals to fix the missing content.



Work around this pattern with our paused tree updates mechanism:

pause tree updates when an unrendered subtree is attached,

until the subtree is fully parsed.

entry.content:
The Automation API custom bindings don't work with service worker-

accessible from the service worker thread.

thread. Instead, the task should be posted to the service worker's

thread.



This CL fixes these issues and cleans up some unneeded data members.

entry.title: Disable system accent-color in image contexts
entry.content:
This patch adds an intervention (behind the flag

`PreventReadingSystemAccentColor`) that disables system accent-color in

image contexts. This prevents leaking the user's system preferences,

which can be used for fingerprinting. Manual tests have been added due

to the difficulty in automated testing of platform-specific theme

painting code.



There are two codepaths that expose the system accent color:

1. Form controls such as checkboxes. This has been disabled with the

code change in `theme_painter_default.cc`.

2. CSS "AccentColor" and "AccentColorText" keywords. These have been

disabled with the code change in `css_parsing.utils.cc`.



Change-Id: Ic650706212b7aaf48b7dcb4923b7f131745bd1ed

entry.title: view-transition: Make new-document opt-in spec-compliant
entry.content:
Update the cross-document opt-in check on a new page to behave according

to the spec. Currently, the transition is skipped if the opt-in state

changes to be disabled, or the opt-in is disabled when the parser

encounters the element. There are two bugs here:



1) crbug.com/1502650 - Without an opt-in, the transition is skipped, but

because the PageRevealEvent's viewTransition object is set when

enqueued, this attribute returns a non-null value even though the

document is opted out.



2) crbug.com/1499122 - Removing the opt-in even after the transition has

started causes the transition to be skipped.



The new behavior is to check the opt-in state once, just before

pagereveal is fired, and skip the transition if needed in this one

place. The PageRevealEvent no longer stores the DOMViewTransition

reference and instead returns the active (navigation based) transition

on the targeted window's document.



root-element-transition-opt-in-removed.html:

This test removes the opt-in from requestAnimationFrame and expects this

to cancel the transition. Since the opt-in is checked in pagereveal, rAF

is now too late so the removal is moved to happen outside the rAF.

entry.title: Pass missed vsyncs to FrameMetricsStore instead of jank status
entry.content:
For each frame metrics received from Android we used to pass it's jank

status to FrameMetricsStore, but this is not enough to answer questions

like what is the maximum jank or total vsyncs missed due to jank. This

change passes missed vsyncs to FrameMetricsStore to do those

calculations like max, count of missed vsyncs.



We can't do exact calculations on number of missed vsyncs since we don't

receive presentation time stamps in webview. We use below formula as

proxy for missed vsyncs.

missed_vsyncs = ceil((total_duration - deadline)/vsync_interval)

total_duration: Total time taken to render the frame.

dealine: Time allocated by system to produce a frame.

entry.title: Remove dependency on //third_party/dawn for Chromium on iOS
entry.content:
Chromium on iOS only depends on a tiny subset of skia and does not

require the //third_party/dawn (except maybe when in the use_blink

experiment), so change skia default configuration to limit when it

depends on dawn.



Note: Chrome on iOS only use a tiny subset of //skia (mostly

SkBitmap, SkColor and SkGraphics for compatibility with the

components that uses those types) as confirmed by the list of

allowed includes in //ios/chrome/DEPS.



//skia when building Chrome on iOS includes files that are not

used by the final executable. The unused code is dropped by the

linker. Changing the build system to reflect that those files

are not used could reduce the number of build steps but is a

huge effort outside of the scope of this change.



The dependency on //third_party/dawn breaks an internal script

as it fails to parse the README.chromium (which lacks a revision

field). Removing the dependency fixes the script.

entry.title: Test overdraw by validating their intended behavior
entry.content:
The 2D canvas overdraw optimization unit tests were implemented by

mocking Canvas2DLayerBridge::WillOverwriteCanvas and checking whether

it's called. This is not testing whether the intended behavior

actually works, it's just testing that the method implementing that

behavior is called, a.k.a. change detector test:

https://testing.googleblog.com/2015/01/testing-on-toilet-change-detector-tests.html



Tests should validate the behavior of the code, not it's implementation:

https://testing.googleblog.com/2013/08/testing-on-toilet-test-behavior-not.html



A follow-up CL will remove Canvas2DLayerBridge::WillOverwriteCanvas.

Instead of moving the mock elsewhere and make another method virtual

just to satisfy unit tests, it's better to fix the unit tests to do the

right thing.

entry.title: Add UMA histogram to diagnose soft nav start time being 0
entry.content:
This is to add 2 UMA histograms to help diagnose soft nav start time

being 0.



One histogram is to record the possible cases that would lead to the

soft nav start time relative to navigation start being 0. This is when

the crash happens. We know this implies that the soft nav start time

relative to reference time is less than or equal to the nav start time

relative to reference time. We want to know how often each case happens.

We also want to know if the soft nav start time relative to reference

time itself could be 0 and if the nav start time itself could be 0.

These are unlikely but we'd like to confirm.



The other histogram is to record cases when soft nav start time

relative to reference time itself is 0. This is unlikely. Cases defined

for this scenario are also unlikely to happen. but we want to confirm.

entry.title: Observable: Implement signal aborting to prep for teardown
entry.content:
Before this CL, `Subscriber#signal` is a dependent signal based

exclusively on `Observer#signal`, if it exists. This means that while

calling `Subscriber#complete()` or `Subscriber#error()` would "close"

the subscription (making `.active` false), but would not abort its

signal.



After this CL, `Subscriber#signal` is a dependent signal based on two

source signals:

1. `Observer#signal`

2. A new signal that gets aborted when `complete()` and `error()` are

called



In response to `Subscriber::signal_` being aborted, the abort algorithm

runs which just calls `Subscriber::CloseSubscription()` (which might

have already been called by this point, if we aborted due to

a `complete()` or `error()` call.



This CL also properly handles the case where `Observer#signal` is

already aborted. Previously, we would not synchronously close down the

subscription, but this CL ensures that we do (see the deleted test

expectations).



This CL is mostly doing preparation for work the `addTeardown()` method

which is used to register teardown callbacks which run as

`Subscriber#signal` gets aborted.
